ts the configuration change is causing the backends to be lost or mismatched somehow.\n\nI'm wondering if the `canary-alt` decoy ingress is interfering. It's configured as a canary with the `X-Canary: beta` header routing, but it points to the stable backend and uses a different hostname that has no primary ingress. Could there be a conflict where both the `canary-canary` and `canary-alt` ingresses are now competing for the same header-based routing logic?\n\nLooking at the 404 error from the logs, it seems to be coming from the default backend rather than the expected upstream, which suggests the request isn't being routed correctly to either the canary or stable service.\n\nThe request size difference (81 bytes vs 99 bytes) indicates whether the canary header was included, but the real issue is that `canary.example.com` isn't matching any server block at all. And there's an error about trying to merge the alternative backend into a hostname that doesn't exist—the canary-alt ingress is failing because it's trying to reference a host that hasn't been properly set up. The `canary-alt` ingress is trying to merge the stable backend into a hostname that doesn't exist as a primary, which triggers the error. The warning about `canary-echo-80` being deleted might be related to how the controller processes the `canary-alt` ingress configuration, which includes canary routing rules with header-based selection. The nginx reload completed successfully at 09:12:45, and after that the canary traffic was working correctly. Then when I made the annotation change, it triggered another reload that broke things—so something about that second reload must have reverted or changed the configuration back to routing through the stable service instead of canary.\n\nI'm wondering if the special value \"always\" for the canary header might take a different code path in the controller than \"beta\" does, which could explain why the behavior changed. But the real puzzle is why changing the annotation would cause the canary to lose its connection to the primary backend entirely. Let me look more closely at that validation log entry to see what configuration was actually accepted. I'm realizing these errors are happening repeatedly as each ingress triggers a sync cycle. The key issue is that when the canary-canary ingress gets validated successfully, the controller immediately fails to find the canary-echo-80 backend, which suggests the backend lookup is failing even though the configuration passed validation. I need to trace through which specific ingress is being processed when this backend lookup error occurs to understand the dependency chain. means the canary ingress `canary-canary` is trying to merge its alternative backend `canary-echo-80` into the primary server for `canary.example.com/`, but the controller can't locate the matching primary backend to attach it to. The primary ingress `canary-stable` should be routing to `stable-echo-80` for that same host, so I'm checking if there's an annotation issue preventing the merge.\n\nLooking at the specs, both ingresses define the same host and path combination (`canary.example.com` with `/` as Exact), so they should match. But I'm noticing that `canary-stable` has multiple paths defined—a `/health` prefix path and a `/` exact path—while `canary-canary` only has the `/` exact path. This path configuration difference might be throwing off the controller's matching logic.\n\nLet me trace through the logs more carefully to see what's actually happening. Before my change, the sequence shows the configuration being validated and accepted, then a sync scheduled, configuration changes detected, and the backend reloaded successfully.\n\nAfter my change, I'm seeing errors about merging alternative backends into hostnames that don't exist, and warnings about real backends not being found for alternative backends. The logs show the system is failing to properly handle the backend configuration during the merge process. Looking at the rest of that error message and the subsequent log entries, I can see the controller is struggling with the alternative backend configuration. It's unable to find the real backend for demo-canary-echo-80 and deletes it, then detects configuration changes that trigger a backend reload. After the reload completes successfully and NGINX restarts, the same merge error resurfaces moments later with the demo-stable-echo-80 backend. The key difference is that with \"always\", the controller was treating `demo-canary-echo-80` as a valid alternative backend, but switching to \"beta\" is causing it to be deleted because it's no longer recognized as part of the configuration. I'm trying to figure out why the primary backend lookup is failing after the annotation change when the actual backend hasn't changed at all. Both requests are hitting the default backend, which means nginx isn't matching `canary.example.com` to any rule at all—suggesting the controller might be rolling back the entire server block when it encounters the canary merge error. The two errors appearing together could indicate they're related, so I should investigate whether deleting and recreating the canary ingress would resolve the conflict. Wait, I'm seeing something important in the timing. That 09:13:38-09:13:40 log was from a sync already queued up, not from my annotation change. The actual sync triggered by my change happened at 09:13:59 when canary-canary was processed. Let me compare what happened before my change - when the 09:12:44 sync of canary-alt also kicked off canary-canary processing, the logs show the configuration validated successfully and the backend reloaded cleanly.\n\nBut after my annotation change at 09:13:39, I'm seeing a \"cannot merge canary-alt\" error and a warning about being unable to find the real backend for canary-echo-80. That warning didn't appear in the earlier reload, which is the critical difference. Switching from \"always\" to \"beta\" is triggering this backend lookup failure. I think the issue is that with \"always\", the controller sends traffic directly to the canary backend, but with \"beta\", it needs to merge the canary backend as an alternative into the primary server block using header-based routing. The merge is failing because the controller can't locate the backend it's trying to reference. I'm wondering if the paths need to match exactly - the stable ingress has both an exact root path and a prefix health path, while the canary only has the exact root path.\n\nLet me try deleting and recreating the canary ingress to see if that resolves it.\n\nActually, I should check the nginx configuration directly to understand what's currently being generated and where these errors are coming from.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2777,"cache_read_input_tokens":31335,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2777},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5ccdfbad-5007-4997-ad8c-322e5804e21d","uuid":"f0929354-0332-4b0f-b1c4-df961f136314","request_id":"req_011Cc6gbvnFPbqCqAbE9EhT8"}
