o the default backend instead.\n\nWhen the canary value was set to \"always\", the controller likely handled it differently—treating it as an unconditional canary rather than a header-based alternative, so it didn't require the same primary backend validation.\n\nBut that doesn't quite add up either, because the stable test at 09:13 showed traffic going to `stable-echo`, not the canary. If \"always\" meant routing everything to canary, the stable requests should have gone there too.\n\nLet me look at the actual access logs more carefully. The format shows the proxy upstream name, alternative upstream name, and the actual backend IP and port. The first request went to `demo-stable-echo-80` with no alternative upstream, hitting `10.244.0.91`. So the stable traffic really was going to the stable backend, not the canary.\n\nThe second request with the X-Canary header went to both `demo-stable-echo-80` and `demo-canary-echo-80`, hitting `10.244.0.92` which is the canary pod. So the canary was actually used for that request.\n\nBut wait, if \"always\" means route ALL traffic to canary, why did the first request (without the header) go to stable? Maybe \"always\" doesn't mean unconditionally route everything—maybe it means \"if the X-Canary header is present with the value 'always', then route to canary.\" Let me check what the nginx-ingress documentation actually says about this behavior. Looking at the actual test logs from 09:13:34 and 09:13:36, the pattern becomes clearer: requests without the header are routing to the stable pod, while requests with the \"X-Canary: beta\" header are routing to the canary pod. This suggests the canary configuration is working as intended, where the header presence (or specific value) determines which backend receives the traffic. the special value \"always\" means all traffic routes to canary regardless of headers, which contradicts what I'm seeing in the logs where requests without headers went to stable. I'm uncertain whether my test